headline.main: Commercial Property; New Jersey Fits the Prescription

docs.lead_paragraph: IF you want to run with the big dogs, you have to go where the big dogs are,'' said Gerald P. Belle, the president of Aventis Pharmaceutical, about the company's decision to shift the operating headquarters of his newly merged company from Kansas City and suburban Philadelphia to Parsippany, N.J. The pharmaceutical industry is in a phase of consolidation as companies seek to spread the cost of developing new drugs over a broader sales base. Increasingly, it is consolidating in New Jersey.

headline.main: James V. Neel Is Dead at 84; Leading Genetics Researcher

docs.abstract: Dr James V Neel, whose work helped uncover genetic basis of sickle cell anemia and who led extensive studies of radiation's effects on survivors of atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, dies at age 84; photo (M)
docs.lead_paragraph: Dr. James V. Neel, whose work helped uncover the genetic basis of sickle cell anemia and who led extensive studies of radiation's effects on the survivors of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, died on Tuesday at his home in Ann Arbor, Mich. He was 84. The cause was cancer, said the University of Michigan, where he was an emeritus professor of human genetics and internal medicine.

headline.main: On Health Report Card, the 'F' Stands for Fat

docs.abstract: Jane E Brody Personal Health column on report that Americans failed to achieve many of health goals established by Surgeon General in 1979 in an ambitious report called Healthy People 2000; notes several of societal goals, like improvements in maternal and child health and fewer deaths from breast cancer and heart disease, were met; says Americans fells short on most of objectives that are under personal control, like diet, exercise and cigarette smoking; notes that new goals outlined in Healthy People 2010 issued by Dr David Satcher, Surgeon General; chart (L)
docs.lead_paragraph: Well, folks, the year 2000 is here and the bad news is that Americans failed to achieve many of the health goals established by the surgeon general in 1979 in an ambitious report called Healthy People 2000. Several of the societal goals, like improvements in maternal and child health and fewer deaths from breast cancer and heart disease, were met. But we fell sadly short on most of the objectives that are under personal control, like diet, exercise and cigarette smoking.
